<exercise id="fs-idp47938160" class="os-exercise">
<problem id="fs-idp37497328">
<!--<para id="fs-idp6364896"><link class="os-embed" url="#ost/api/ex/k12phys-ch04-ex018"/></para>-->

<para id="fs-id1164567519111">What does Newtons first law state?</para>
<list id="fs-id1164567104467" list-type="enumerated" number-style="lower-alpha">
<item>A body at rest tends to remain at rest and a body in motion tends to remain in motion at a constant acceleration unless acted on by a net external force.</item>
<item>A body at rest tends to remain at rest and a body in motion tends to remain in motion at a constant velocity unless acted on by a net external force.</item>
<item>The rate of change of momentum of a body is directly proportional to the external force applied to the body.</item>
<item>The rate of change of momentum of a body is inversely proportional to the external force applied to the body.</item>
</list>
</problem></exercise>
<exercise id="fs-idp97846624" class="os-exercise"><problem id="fs-idp36060656">
<!--<para id="fs-idp44588800"><link class="os-embed" url="#ost/api/ex/k12phys-ch04-ex019"/></para>-->
<para id="fs-id1164567528034">According to Newtons first law, a body in motion tends to remain in motion at a constant velocity. However, when you slide an object across a surface, the object eventually slows down and stops. Why?</para>
<list id="fs-id1164567089656" list-type="enumerated" number-style="lower-alpha">
<item>The object experiences a frictional force exerted by the surface, which opposes its motion.</item>
<item>The object experiences the gravitational force exerted by Earth, which opposes its motion</item>
<item>The object experiences an internal force exerted by the body itself, which opposes its motion.</item>
<item>The object experiences a pseudo-force from the body in motion, which opposes its motion.</item>
</list>
</problem></exercise>
<exercise id="fs-idp72241184" class="os-exercise"><problem id="fs-idp53190224"><para id="fs-idp54736096"><link class="os-embed" url="#ost/api/ex/k12phys-ch04-ex020"/></para></problem></exercise>
<exercise id="fs-idp86925600" class="os-exercise"><problem id="fs-idp30536672">
<!--<para id="fs-idm16321040"><link class="os-embed" url="#ost/api/ex/k12phys-ch04-ex021"/></para>-->

<para id="fs-id1164567999263">What is mass? What does it depend on?</para>
<list id="fs-id1164567620406" list-type="enumerated" number-style="lower-alpha">
<item>Mass is the weight of an object, and it depends on the gravitational force acting on the object.</item>
<item>Mass is the weight of an object, and it depends on the number and types of atoms in the object.</item>
<item>Mass is the quantity of matter contained in an object, and it depends on the gravitational force acting on the object.</item>
<item>Mass is the quantity of matter contained in an object, and it depends on the number and types of atoms in the object.</item>
</list>
</problem></exercise>
