</exercise></section><section id="fs-idm69695760" class="critical-thinking">
<title>Critical Thinking</title>
<exercise id="fs-idp5127360" class="os-exercise"><problem id="fs-idp16956768">
<!--<para id="fs-idm57894784"><link class="os-embed" url="#ost/api/ex/k12phys-ch04-ex024"/></para>-->
<para id="fs-id1164567164532">Two people push a cart on a horizontal surface by applying forces F<sub>1</sub>  and F<sub>2</sub> in the same direction. Is the magnitude of the net force acting on the cart, F<sub>net</sub>, equal to, greater than, or less than F<sub>1</sub> + F<sub>2</sub>? Why?</para>
<list id="fs-id1164567409294" list-type="enumerated" number-style="lower-alpha">
<item>F<sub>net</sub> &lt; F<sub>1</sub> + F<sub>2</sub> because the net force will not include the frictional force.</item>
<item>F<sub>net</sub> = F<sub>1</sub> + F<sub>2</sub> because the net force will not include the frictional force</item>
<item>F<sub>net</sub> &lt; F<sub>1</sub> + F<sub>2</sub> because the net force will include the component of frictional force</item>
<item>F<sub>net</sub> = F<sub>1</sub> + F<sub>2</sub> because the net force will include the frictional force</item>
</list>

</problem></exercise>
